Rx question: I have a bunch of methods that do api calls. They should return Observable<SomeReturnType>. That's easy. But I also want to have the internal api handler to buffer requests. So in theory what I want is to feed those api call observables into some other observable that does the server request buffering. Does that make sense, and if so, is that even possible?
Using a PublishSubject doesn't make sense since it would emit the results of all api calls to all currently subscribed Subscribers
I want to basically bundle up to X api calls into one server request, yet to deliver the result of each to the correct caller.
Almost everything is possible with Rx. You just have to find the right functions.
Are you just trying to abstract something that happens on all requests or are you actually trying to have them converge into one place when the actual rest call is made?
Yep, there is one place where the final call to the server is made
The api supports a list of operations, so I want to bundle up to x requests
So I thought to use `buffer()` and then just do the request with the emitted list.
And then you will just split up the response and you want to return them to the appropriate location
Correct

Been trying all kinds of things for 2h now :smile:
Well you can get them all together with .zip()
Then possibly return by calling .call on a custom subscriber in the .subscribe() of your actual rest call
